Certainly! Here's a simple JavaScript program that generates and prints ASCII characters along with their corresponding hexadecimal codes for numbers from 0 to 7F:

```javascript
// Function to convert decimal to ASCII and hexadecimal
function decimalToHexadecimal(charCode) {
    return `Unicode (ASCII): ${charCode} - Character: ${String.fromCharCode(charCode)}\nHexadecimal: 0x${charCode.toString(16).toUpperCase()}`;
}

// Iterate through numbers 0 to 7F
for (let i = 0; i <= 7; i++) {
    // Get the ASCII code for the character at position i
    const charCode = i;

    // Print the ASCII and hexadecimal codes
    console.log(decimalToHexadecimal(charCode));
}
```

This program defines a function `decimalToHexadecimal` that takes an ASCII decimal code as input, converts it to both the corresponding character and its hexadecimal representation. Then, it loops through numbers 0 to 7 (which represent the characters from space to lowercase '!', inclusive), calculates their ASCII codes, and prints the results using the function.

When you run this script in a browser's JavaScript console or an environment like Node.js, it will display the ASCII and hexadecimal codes for each character.
